{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6fb6446a-19d3-4a32-b39a-7e8e91bbfaed","content":"The project doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- Makes this a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key properties explained\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the project as a .NET tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users run (e.g., `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `PackageId` | The NuGet package name |\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server\n```\n\nSince your server uses **stdio transport**, users will typically configure it in their MCP client (e.g., VS Code) with a `command`/`args` entry pointing to the tool command name.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b5b3dab8-0314-4af8-ae0f-66a1e68bc1c7","outputTokens":505,"requestId":"F413:1D6FD0:1AB2415:1D87B15:69FDA93F"},"id":"6d5d9a30-e219-41c3-b137-a30515c8ba55","timestamp":"2026-05-08T09:13:52.306Z","parentId":"2087d0d7-20bb-467e-8677-e4735decae98"}
